{"key":"processedPost-6844355","value":{"id":6844355,"first":6841915,"last":6844580,"when":1177765222,"utime":"04/28/07 04:00 PM","cleanedPost":"Once pins are set, the fruits tend to grow more in the period of darkness, but I haven't found a correlation with less light equals bigger or smaller fruits.  12/12 still seems to be the best all around light cycle.<br />Lower temperatures tend to slow growth, leading to a higher quality end product.<br />High humidity protects the fruits from drying out with the resulting cracked caps, however scaling as it's often called is considered desirable with some species such as shiitake, so it certainly doesn't hurt.  However, low humidity also speeds up drying of the substrate and casing layer, which causes smaller fruits.<br />RR"}}